data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` likewise removed** — no equivalent needed
3. **`default(T)` for reference types is `null`** — same, but nullable warnings will surface

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// Pass the token into your work delegate so it can exit cleanly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, honoring the timeout.
            // If the task faults, this unwraps the AggregateException.
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            // Cancel and give the task a short window to observe it.
            cts.Cancel();
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Convenience overload when the work ignores cancellation (fire-and-forget on timeout).
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced abort** | .NET 8 has no way to kill a thread. Cancellation is *cooperative* — your `work` must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O calls. Without this, the work keeps running after timeout. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | It throws `TimeoutException` when the timeout elapses, even if the underlying task is still running. This replaces the `Thread.Join(timeout)` pattern. |
| **Thread pool vs. dedicated thread** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. If your work does long blocking (as the original suggests), consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to avoid starving the pool. |
| **Exception wrapping changed** | The original threw `AggregateException`. The migrated version unwraps via `GetAwaiter().GetResult()`, throwing the inner exception directly. If callers catch `AggregateException`, update them. |

### If You Truly Need Hard Abort (Escape Hatch)

For legacy code you can't make cooperative, isolate it in a **separate process** and kill the process on timeout — this is the only safe forced-termination in .NET 8:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution
var proc = Process.Start("MyWorker.exe", args);
if (!proc.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    proc.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Usage Example

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Cooperative — best practice
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // ... do a chunk of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**Bottom line:** Replace `Thread.Abort` with `CancellationToken`. There is no equivalent to forced thread abort in modern .NET — design for cooperative cancellation.
